I’m so sorry about your dad. Please take good care of yourself – I’m thinking about you.

The most important thing is not about the money but about the closure and the relationship dynamics. Let me try to help you understand why your father might have left you everything.

Your father might have wanted to support you financially to make up for the absence during your childhood. He might have seen the inheritance as a way to express his love and regret for not being there. It’s possible he thought you deserved more because he didn’t have the chance to do more for you when you were younger.

Maya is handling this her way by not contesting the will. She’s choosing to let go of the inheritance to respect her father’s wishes. It doesn’t mean she resents you. She understands that her father wanted you to have the money as a form of support and perhaps a way to right past wrongs.

You can’t control his motives or the distribution – the will is legal and valid. What you can do is decide how you want to carry on his legacy. Think about whether you want to keep the inheritance, donate some or all of it to causes he believed in, or help Maya in a different way.

The letter is probably from him explaining his decision. It’s okay to take your time with it. When you’re ready, read it in a place where you feel safe and can process your emotions.

Remember, the inheritance is not about deserving but about completing your relationship with your father. It’s a financial gift but also an emotional one. How you choose to handle it can be a tribute to the complex relationship you had with him.

You can find solace in knowing that the money was given out of guilt or love, but the decision on how to use it is yours. It’s okay to feel uncertain – it’s a big change. Take your time to figure out what feels right for you. And know that I’m thinking of you – take good care.
